  <h1>Research</h1>

  <p>
    I work on <strong>efficient multimodal models</strong> — vision–language
    models that have to run under a fixed compute or token budget. A lot of
    recent work compresses the visual tokens a model sees (merging, pruning,
    pooling) and reports that average benchmark accuracy holds up. I'm
    interested in the part that average accuracy hides: <em>which</em>
    capabilities break first under compression, and whether the failure looks
    like dropped information or confidently wrong information.
  </p>

  <h2>Interests</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Visual-token compression for VLMs (merging, pruning, pooling).</li>
    <li>Capability-specific degradation under a fixed token budget.</li>
    <li>Failure modes: omission vs. hallucination, and what causes which.</li>
  </ul>

